{"questionId":"13101","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f'\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msup>\n    <mi>f</mi>\n    <mo>′</mo>\n  </msup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, 0 ≤ <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp;≤ 5 is shown in the following diagram. The curve intercepts the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>-axis at (1, 0) and (4, 0) and has a local minimum at (3, −1).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/3cbb4bffa894dd2e849244395cf6acc76f04a7ec.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span>-coordinate of the point of inflexion on the graph of&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\"> <mi>y</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>f</mi> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mi>x</mi> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p style=\"color:#999;font-size:90%;font-style:italic;\">* This question is from an exam for a previous syllabus, and may contain minor differences in marking or structure.</p>\n<p>3&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13101","referenceCode":"19M.1.AHL.TZ1.H_8a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Write down the x -coordinate of the point of inflexion on the graph of y = f ( x ) .","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Prior learning","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative"],"me